      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(mattermost): backfill thread history from server when in-memory window is empty",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Mattermost now backfills thread history from the server when its in-memory history window is empty, so a bot re-mentioned inside an existing thread after a restart/session-clear replies **with** context instead of blind.\n- Non-thread / main-channel messages are unaffected; backfill failures are logged and degrade gracefully to the prior behavior.\n\n## Motivation\n\nCloses #93204 (split from umbrella #65729).\n\nMattermost thread/conversation history is **in-memory only**. After a gateway restart or a session clear, the in-memory history window for a thread is empty. So when a user `@mentions` the bot inside an existing thread to wake it, the agent replies with zero thread context — most acute exactly when it matters: the bot was unresponsive (token expiry, restart) and the user re-mentions it inside the thread to recover.\n\nThis adds the missing **\"in-memory history empty → fetch the thread from the server\"** recovery path described in the issue.\n\n## What changed\n\nWhen handling a thread message (`root_id` present) whose in-memory history for that `historyKey` is empty:\n1. Fetch the full thread via `GET /posts/{threadRootId}/thread`.\n2. Map `order` → `posts` into history entries — resolving usernames (falling back to user id), skipping the current post, system posts, and empty (no body / no files) posts.\n3. Seed the history window with the last *N* entries (trimmed to the configured `historyLimit`).\n\nImplementation:\n- `fetchMattermostThread` client helper + `MattermostThreadSchema` (zod) in `client.ts`.\n- `buildThreadBackfillEntries` — a pure, network-free mapper in `thread-backfill.ts` (kept separate so it is unit-testable under the mocked-SDK test shim).\n- Wired into the monitor inbound path right before context assembly, guarded by `threadRootId && historyLimit > 0 && window empty`. Wrapped in try/catch — a failed fetch logs verbosely and falls back to the prior blind-reply behavior rather than dropping the message.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** A bot re-mentioned inside an existing Mattermost thread after a restart/session-clear (empty in-memory history window) replied with zero thread context. This patch adds the \"empty window → reconstruct from the server-fetched thread\" recovery path (the core mapper `buildThreadBackfillEntries`), seeding the history window from `GET /posts/{rootId}/thread`.\n- **Real environment tested:** Live OpenClaw instance on this host — macOS (Darwin 25.4.0, arm64), node v25.5.0 — executing the **shipped** `extensions/mattermost/src/mattermost/thread-backfill.ts` from the PR branch via the repo's own `tsx` runner. No mocks of the function under test; it was driven with a realistic thread payload that mirrors the recovery scenario (a re-mention wake post, a system join post, a whitespace-only post, a file-only post, and prior human/bot turns).\n- **Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n  ```\n  # from repo root on branch fix/93204-mattermost-thread-backfill\n  npx tsx proof-mm-backfill.mts\n  # driver imports the shipped buildThreadBackfillEntries and runs it with\n  # currentPostId=p_now (the wake re-mention), limit=3 (historyLimit),\n  # a username lookup, and the system-post predicate.\n  ```\n- **Evidence after fix:** Copied live terminal/console output from the run of the shipped function:\n  ```\n  RESULT buildThreadBackfillEntries (limit=3, currentPostId=p_now):\n  [\n    {\n      \"sender\": \"bartok-bot\",\n      \"body\": \"Sure — pulling the latest grazing data now.\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1718440002000,\n      \"messageId\": \"p2\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"sender\": \"alice\",\n      \"body\": \"Great, thanks!\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1718440004000,\n      \"messageId\": \"p3\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"sender\": \"daniel\",\n      \"body\": \"[Mattermost file]\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1718440005000,\n      \"messageId\": \"p_file\"\n    }\n  ]\n\n  ASSERTIONS:\n    current re-mention skipped (no p_now): true\n    system post skipped (no p_sys): true\n    whitespace-only post skipped (no p_empty): true\n    trimmed to last 3: true\n    file-only post → placeholder body: [Mattermost file]\n    display names resolved (not raw ids): true\n  ```\n- **Observed result after fix:** The empty-window recovery path produced a correctly reconstructed history window: the wake re-mention (`p_now`) is excluded, the `system_add_to_channel` post and the whitespace-only post are dropped, the file-only post renders as `[Mattermost file]`, sender ids resolve to display names (`u_dan`→`daniel`, etc.), and the window is trimmed to the last 3 entries per `historyLimit`. This is exactly the context the agent would now have on a thread re-mention after a restart instead of replying blind. Before the patch this path did not exist, so the window stayed empty.\n- **What was not tested:** End-to-end against a live Mattermost server instance (the network `fetchMattermostThread` round-trip) — that path is covered by the unit test exercising the request/parse shape, and the mapper consuming its output is proven live above.\n\n## Supplemental checks\n\n- `npx vitest run --config test/vitest/vitest.extension-mattermost.config.ts` — **489 passed** (41 files), including 8 new `thread-backfill.test.ts` cases.\n- `npx tsc -p tsconfig.extensions.json --noEmit` — clean.\n- `oxfmt` applied to all changed files.\n\n## Did NOT change\n\n- Main-channel / non-thread inbound handling.\n- Direct-message handling (`historyKey` is null for DMs).\n- The existing in-memory `record`/`buildPendingContext`/`buildInboundHistory` flow — backfill only *seeds* the empty window; once seeded, normal recording continues.\n",
        "branch": "fix/93204-mattermost-thread-backfill",
